        "### Fit Uncertainty Model\n",
        "\n",
        "This part aims to estimate the incertitude of the outputted reflectance of SMAC using lightweight and fast Neural Network. Those models will be exclusively Feed Forward Neural Network (also called MLP) and will be small to satisfy hardware constraint on memory usage.\n",
        "\n",
        "The required library for the inference of ML model is ONNXRuntime. It is a library that optimizes and executes machine learning models in ONNX (Open Neural Network Exchange) format. In operational workflows, it enables fast, efficient model deployment by opening model as black-box function.\n",
        "\n",
        "[Inputs]{.underline} :\n",
        "\n",
        "- Angles (SZA, VZA, RAA)\n",
        "\n",
        "- AOD at 550 nm\n",
        "\n",
        "- Pression\n",
        "\n",
        "- TOC-r\n",
        "\n",
        "- iaer\n",
        "\n",
        "- TOA-r\n",
        "\n",
        "After using the SMAC coefficients simulations representing more than 106 points, we performed a test using a very fast pots processing pure python NN inference for one band. The test outcome, shown hereafter, is promising to show a Mean Square Error of 0.0097 on the predicted RTM uncertainty on R~toc~\n",
        "\n",
        "> ![](./media/media/image16.png){width=\"6.3in\" height=\"2.3506944444444446in\"}\n",
        "\n",
        "## BRDF effect estimation\n",
        "\n",
        "The baseline AC are run under the assumption of a lambertian surface. If the shape of the surface BRDF is known, we can optionally include this knowledge into the AC scheme with the following modelling\n",
        "\n",
        "### Surface BRDF model (RossThick-LiSparse-R)\n",
        "\n",
        "In the following, we restrict the description to a model with three parameters of the form:\n",
        "\n",
        "+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n",
        "|                                                                                             |\n",
        "+:============================================================================================+\n",
        "| $\\rho_{g}$*(θ~s~, θ~v~, ϕ) = k~0~ + k~1~F~1~(θ~s~, θ~v~, ϕ) + k~2~F~2~(θ~s~, θ~v~, ϕ)* (25) |\n",
        "+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n",
        "\n",
        "------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "\n",
        "While *k~0~* quantifies an isotropic contribution to the reflectance factor *F~0~*=1, functions *F~1~* and *F~2~* represent the angular distribution related to geometric and volumetric surface scattering processes, respectively. Lucht et al. (2000) suggest the RossThick-LiSparse-Reciprocal model (simply referred to as the Ross-Li BRDF model) that results from the combination of two models for the definition of the volumetric (RossThick) and geometric (LiSparse-R) kernels. The geometric kernel is expressed as follows:\n",
        "\n",
        "+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n",
        "|                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        |\n",
        "+:=======================================================================================================================================================================================================================================================================================================+\n",
        "| $$F_{1}\\left( \\theta_{s}{,\\theta}_{v},\\phi \\right) = O\\left( \\theta_{s}{,\\theta}_{v},\\phi \\right) - sec\\left( {\\theta\\ '}_{s} \\right) - sec\\left( {\\theta\\ }_{v}^{'} \\right) + \\frac{1}{2}\\left( 1 + cos(\\xi\\ ') \\right)\\sec\\left( {\\theta\\ '}_{s} \\right)\\sec\\left( {\\theta\\ }_{v}^{'} \\right)$$ (26) |\n",
        "+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n",
        "\n",
        "------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "\n",
        "Where,\n",
        "\n",
        "+----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+---------+\n",
        "| $$O = \\frac{1}{\\pi}\\left( t - sin(t)\\cos(t) \\right)\\left( \\sec\\left( \\theta_{s}^{\\ '} \\right) - sec\\left( \\theta_{v}^{\\ '} \\right) \\right)$$                                                                         | \\(27\\)  |\n",
        "+:=====================================================================================================================================================================================================================+:========+\n",
        "| $$\\cos{(t) = 2}\\frac{\\sqrt{D^{2} + \\left( \\tan\\left( \\theta_{s}^{\\ '} \\right)\\tan\\left( \\theta_{v}^{\\ '} \\right)\\sin(\\phi) \\right)^{2}}}{\\sec\\left( \\theta_{s}^{\\ '} \\right) + sec\\left( \\theta_{v}^{\\ '} \\right)}$$ | \\(28\\)  |\n",
        "+----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+---------+\n",
        "| $$D = \\sqrt{\\tan^{2}\\left( \\theta_{s}^{\\ '} \\right) + \\tan^{2}\\left( \\theta_{v}^{\\ '} \\right) - 2tan\\left( \\theta_{s}^{\\ '} \\right)\\tan\\left( \\theta_{v}^{\\ '} \\right)\\cos(\\phi)}$$                                  | \\(29\\)  |\n",
        "+----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+---------+\n",
        "| $$\\cos\\left( \\xi^{\\ '} \\right) = cos\\left( \\theta_{s}^{\\ '} \\right)\\cos\\left( \\theta_{v}^{\\ '} \\right) + sin\\left( \\theta_{s}^{\\ '} \\right)\\sin\\left( \\theta_{v}^{\\ '} \\right)\\cos(\\phi)$$                           | \\(30\\)  |\n",
        "+----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+---------+\n",
        "| $\\theta_{s}^{\\ '} = \\tan^{- 1}\\left( \\frac{b_{RL}}{r}\\tan\\theta_{s} \\right)$ and $\\theta_{v}^{\\ '} = \\tan^{- 1}\\left( \\frac{b_{RL}}{r}\\tan\\theta_{v} \\right)$                                                        | \\(31\\)  |\n",
        "+----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+---------+\n",
        "\n",
        "And the volumetric kernel is defined as:\n",
        "\n",
        "+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n",
        "|                                                                                                                                                                                                         |\n",
        "+:========================================================================================================================================================================================================+\n",
        "| $$F_{2}\\left( \\theta_{s}{,\\theta}_{v},\\phi \\right) = \\frac{\\left( \\frac{\\pi}{2} - \\xi \\right)\\cos(\\xi) + sin(\\xi)}{\\cos\\left( \\theta_{s} \\right) + cos\\left( \\theta_{v} \\right)} - \\frac{\\pi}{4}$$ (32) |\n",
        "+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n",
        "\n",
        "------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "\n",
        "Where\n",
        "\n",
        "+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n",
        "|                                                                                                                                                                                            |\n",
        "+:===========================================================================================================================================================================================+\n",
        "| $$\\cos\\left( \\xi^{\\ } \\right) = cos\\left( \\theta_{s}^{\\ } \\right)\\cos\\left( \\theta_{v}^{\\ } \\right) + sin\\left( \\theta_{s}^{\\ } \\right)\\sin\\left( \\theta_{v}^{\\ } \\right)\\cos(\\phi)$$ (33) |\n",
        "+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n",
        "\n",
        "------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "\n",
        "The choice is used here: *h/b~RL~*=2 and *b~RL~/r*=1.\n",
        "\n",
        "We can summarize the surface BRDF modelling as:\n",
        "\n",
        "+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+-----------+\n",
        "| $$\\rho_{g} = k_{0}\\left\\lbrack 1 + k_{1}^{p}F_{1} + k_{2}^{p}F_{2} \\right\\rbrack$$                | \\(34\\)    |\n",
        "|                                                                                                   |           |\n",
        "| with $k_{1}^{p} = \\frac{k_{1}}{k_{0}} ;\\ k_{2}^{p} = \\frac{k_{2}}{k_{0}}$ |           |\n",
        "+===================================================================================================+===========+\n",
        "|                                                                                                   |           |\n",
        "+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+-----------+\n",
        "\n",
        "kp's are normalized coefficients that describe the departure from the lambertian reflector (in that case${\\ k}_{1}^{p} = k_{2}^{p} = 0$**), this is the baseline processing**.\n",
        "\n",
        "phic correction including BRDF effects\n",
        "\n",
        "### Fast radiative transfer model with BRDF\n",
        "\n",
        "In the case of a horizontally homogeneous target, the surface BRDF shape can be included through the 6S formulation (*Vermote et al., 1997*), and the atmospheric correction equations \\[2-4\\] are the same except that we have a modified total atmospheric transmission $T_{atm;g}$(*Ramon and Santer, 2001*):\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "T_{atm;g} = \\left( 1 - D\\left( \\mu_{v} \\right) \\right)\\left( 1 - D\\left( \\mu_{s} \\right) \\right) + \\frac{\\overline{\\rho_{g}}}{\\rho_{g}}\\left( 1 - D\\left( \\mu_{v} \\right) \\right)D\\left( \\mu_{s} \\right)\n",
        "+ \\frac{\\overline{\\rho_{g}}'}{\\rho_{g}}D\\left( \\mu_{v} \\right)\\left( 1 - D\\left( \\mu_{s} \\right) \\right) + \\frac{\\overline{\\overline{\\rho_{g}}}}{\\rho_{g}}D\\left( \\mu_{v} \\right)D\\left( \\mu_{s} \\right)\n",
        "$$\n",
        "(35)\n",
        "\n",
        "------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "\n",
        "Where *D* is the ratio of diffuse over total transmission and $\\ \\overline{\\rho_{g}}\\ \\ and\\ \\overline{\\overline{\\rho_{g}}}$ are single and double directional weighted averages of the surface BRDF. The weight is the atmospheric downward radiance$\\ L_{atm}^{\\downarrow}$ at the ground level:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\overline{\\rho_{g}} = \\overline{\\rho_{g}}(\\theta_{s}{,\\theta}_{v},\\phi) = \\frac{\\int_{0}^{2\\pi}{\\int_{0}^{\\frac{\\pi}{2}}{\\cos\\theta^{'}L_{atm}^{\\downarrow}\\left( \\theta_{s}{,\\ \\theta}^{'},\\varphi^{'} \\right)\\rho_{g}\\left( \\theta^{'},\\theta_{v},\\varphi^{'} - \\phi \\right)\\sin{\\theta^{'}d\\theta^{'}d\\varphi^{'}}}}}{\\int_{0}^{2\\pi}{\\int_{0}^{\\frac{\\pi}{2}}{\\cos{\\theta^{'}L_{atm}^{\\downarrow}\\left( \\theta_{s}{,\\ \\theta}^{'},\\varphi^{'} \\right)}}}\\sin{\\theta^{'}d\\theta^{'}d\\varphi^{'}}} \\quad (36)\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where ${\\overline{\\rho_{g}}}^{'}\\left( \\theta_{s}{,\\theta}_{v},\\phi \\right) = \\overline{\\rho_{g}}(\\theta_{v}{,\\theta}_{s},\\phi)$ and \n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\overline{\\overline{\\rho_{g}}} = \\overline{\\overline{\\rho_{g}}}\\left( \\theta_{s}{,\\theta}_{v},\\phi \\right) = \\overline{{\\overline{\\rho_{g}}}^{'}\\left( \\theta_{s}{,\\theta}_{v},\\phi \\right)}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "\n",
        "The linearization of the ground reflectance allows the ground to derive depending on terms as a function of just kernel directional averages $\\overline{F_{1}},\\overline{F_{2}},\\overline{\\overline{F_{1}}},\\overline{\\overline{F_{2}}}$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{aligned}\n",
        "\\overline{\\rho_{g}} &= k_{0}\\left\\lbrack 1 + k_{1}^{p}\\overline{F_{1}} + k_{2}^{p}\\overline{F_{2}} \\right\\rbrack \\\\\n",
        "\\overline{\\overline{\\rho_{g}}} &= k_{0}\\left\\lbrack 1 + k_{1}^{p}\\overline{\\overline{F_{1}}} + k_{2}^{p}\\overline{\\overline{F_{2}}} \\right\\rbrack\n",
        "\\end{aligned} \\quad (37)\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\frac{\\overline{\\rho_{g}}}{\\rho_{g}} = \\frac{1 + k_{1}^{p}{\\overline{F}}_{1} + k_{2}^{p}{\\overline{F}}_{2}}{1 + k_{1}^{p}F_{1} + k_{2}^{p}F_{2}} \\quad (38)\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "\n",
        "+----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n",
        "|                                                                                                                                                                |\n",
        "+:===============================================================================================================================================================+\n",
        "| $$\\frac{\\overline{\\rho_{g}}'}{\\rho_{g}} = \\ \\frac{1 + k_{1}^{p}{\\overline{F}}_{1}' + k_{2}^{p}{\\overline{F}}_{2}'}{1 + k_{1}^{p}F_{1} + k_{2}^{p}F_{2}}$$ (39) |\n",
        "+----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n",
        "\n",
        "------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "\n",
        "+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n",
        "|                                                                                                                                                                                            |\n",
        "+:===========================================================================================================================================================================================+\n",
        "| $$\\frac{\\overline{\\overline{\\rho_{g}}}}{\\rho_{g}} = \\ \\frac{1 + k_{1}^{p}\\overline{\\overline{F_{1}}} + k_{2}^{p}{\\overline{\\overline{F}}}_{2}}{1 + k_{1}^{p}F_{1} + k_{2}^{p}F_{2}}$$ (40) |\n",
        "+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n",
        "\n",
        "------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "\n",
        "The estimation of BRDF effects requires the knowledge of $k_{1}^{p}$ and${\\ k}_{2}^{p}$, the kernels and their directional averages are analytically computed\n",
        "\n",
        "SMAC general philosophy is to approximate atmospheric functions with simple and fast regression. We thus analysed the variations of the kernel directional averages as a function of wavelength and aerosol optical thickness. The computation has been made with exact radiative transfer computations for the downward atmospheric radiances and integration using Equations (38). Figure 10 and Figure 11 show some examples of $\\overline{{\\ F}_{1}},\\overline{F_{2}},\\overline{\\overline{F_{1}}},\\overline{\\overline{F_{2}}}$ in the NIR for one aerosol model and 2 AOTs as well as the case where the sky radiance is supposed isotropic. In the latter case the kernel directional single (resp. double) integral is simply the hemispherical-directional (resp. bi hemispherical) albedo. Directionality is still pronounced for single integrals, and smooth for double ones. It is mainly dependent on wavelength and not AOT and the directional behaviour is like the kernels themselves. So the idea here is to make a computation of $\\overline{{\\ F}_{1}},\\overline{F_{2}},\\overline{\\overline{F_{1}}},\\overline{\\overline{F_{2}}}$ as linear combinations of the kernels F~1~ and F~2~, the coefficients of the combinations being only functions of the spectral channel.\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{aligned}\n",
        "{\\overline{F}}_{1} &= d_{1}^{0} + d_{1}^{1}\\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{1}} + d_{1}^{2}\\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{2}} \\\\\n",
        "{\\overline{F}}_{2} &= d_{2}^{0} + d_{2}^{1}\\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{1}} + d_{2}^{2}\\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{2}} \\\\\n",
        "\\overline{\\overline{F_{1}}} &= b_{1}^{0} + b_{1}^{1}\\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{1}} + b_{1}^{2}\\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{2}} \\\\\n",
        "{\\overline{\\overline{F}}}_{2} &= b_{2}^{0} + b_{2}^{1}\\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{1}} + b_{2}^{2}\\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{2}} \\\\\n",
        "{\\overline{F}}_{1}^{'} &= d_{1}^{0} + d_{1}^{1}\\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{1}}^{'} + d_{1}^{2}\\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{2}}^{'} \\\\\n",
        "{\\overline{F}}_{2}^{'} &= d_{2}^{0} + d_{2}^{1}\\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{1}}^{'} + d_{2}^{2}\\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{2}}^{'}\n",
        "\\end{aligned} \\quad (41)\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "\n",
        "Where, by convention:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{aligned}\n",
        "{\\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{1}} &= F}_{1}\\left( \\theta_{s}{,\\theta}_{v},\\phi \\right) \\\\\n",
        "{\\mathbf{F}_{\\mathbf{2}} &= F}_{2}\\left( \\theta_{s}{,\\theta}_{v},\\phi \\right) \\\\\n",
        "{\\mathbf{F'}_{\\mathbf{1}} &= F}_{1}\\left( \\theta_{v}{,\\theta}_{s},\\phi \\right) \\\\\n",
        "{\\mathbf{F'}_{\\mathbf{2}} &= F}_{2}\\left( \\theta_{v}{,\\theta}_{s},\\phi \\right)\n",
        "\\end{aligned} \\quad (42)\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
        "\n",
        "The 12 regressions coefficients $d_{i}^{k}$ and $b_{i}^{k}$ are stored in the SMAC coefficient's structure. F~1~ and F~2~ are analytical functions, computed once per pixel. Therefore, the corrective BRDF terms are calculated extremely fast.\n",
        "\n",
        "The accuracy of such modelling has been checked against exact computations and compared to the accuracy of the lambertian assumption. A typical example is given in Figure 12 and Figure 13 for a scene that consists of a vegetation target in the NIR with a high aerosol load, where the BRDF effects are the highest. On can see that the lambertian assumption leads to directional biases that could reach 10% for oblique views and SZA=60°. Our simple model significantly reduces the intensity and directional dependence of those biases.\n",
        "\n",
        "+---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n",
        "| ![](./media/media/image17.png){width=\"5.822834645669292in\" height=\"2.4960629921259843in\"} |\n",
        "+:============================================================================================================================================================================================+\n",
