        "# Appendix B: Aerosol Model Definitions\n",
        "\n",
        "## Aerosol variability on Earth\n",
        "\n",
        "44 688 MERRA-2 grid points have been selected over land. Four dates have been chosen to represent the seasonal variability: 2011/01/01, 2011/04/01, 2011/07/01, and 2011/10/01. Data is taken at 13:00.\n",
        "\n",
        "Global average of AOT is computed for each component for the four dates. The total AOT increases from winter to summer, especially because of desert dust and OC. Indeed, desert dust AOT increases from 0.04 to 0.10 and OC AOT from 0.02 to 0.05. The three other components AOT vary little with the season.\n",
        "\n",
        "The aerosol models are defined according to the MERRA-2 5 AOT ratios of each aerosol component u {X~u~, u$\\  \\in \\{ DU,SU,OC,BC,SS\\ \\}$}:\n",
        "\n",
        "X~u~ = $\\frac{\\mathbf{\\tau}_{\\mathbf{a}\\mathbf{;}\\mathbf{u}}^{\\mathbf{550}}}{\\mathbf{\\tau}_{\\mathbf{a}}^{\\mathbf{550}}}$\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.content-visible when-format=\"docx\"}\n",
        "![](./media/media/image27.emf){width=\"6.075in\" height=\"7.541666666666667in\"}\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.content-visible when-format=\"pdf\"}\n",
        "*(Figure omitted in PDF export: original table is a Windows EMF vector graphic not convertible in this environment; see the DOCX version of this ATBD for the figure.)*\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Table : Statistics about AOT's of each aerosol component from MERRA-2 analysis of 4 days in 2011\n",
        "\n",
        "Each mixing ratio X~u~ covers the 0-100% range except BC which remains smaller than 25% on the four dates. The SU, DU, OC and SS X~u~ are defined between 0 and 100% with steps of 20%, and the BC X~u~ is defined between 0 and 30% with a step of 5%.\n",
        "\n",
        "From the 5x5x5x5x6=3750 possible combinations, 148 combinations of the component X~u~ effectively occur on the 44 688 pixels of 2011/07/01. These 148 combinations of the components X~u~ define 148 aerosol models. (See Figure 14)\n",
        "\n",
        "![](./media/media/image28.png){width=\"6.146489501312336in\" height=\"3.7656889763779526in\"}\n",
        "\n",
        "Figure : AOT's ratio's X~u~ of the 5 MERRA-2 aerosol components of the 148 aerosol model used in this study\n",
        "\n",
        "## Aerosol optical properties\n",
        "\n",
        "To calculate easily the optical properties of these mixing, we directly associate one OPAC aerosol model/component with each component u from MERRA-2 (see Table 13). For the moment the relative humidity is considered fixed to 80%\n",
        "\n",
        "Table : Mapping between MERRA-2 aerosol component and OPAC for the computation of optical properties\n",
        "\n",
        "| **MERRA-2 aerosol component** | **OPAC model or component (RH=80%)** |\n",
        "|:------------------------------|:-------------------------------------|\n",
        "| SU/SU                         | Antarctic model                      |\n",
        "| DU/DU                         | Desert model                         |\n",
        "| OC/OM                         | Water soluble (waso) component       |\n",
        "| SS/SS                         | Maritime clean model                 |\n",
        "| BC/BC                         | Soot component                       |\n",
        "\n",
        "The aerosol optical properties necessary for SMAC are then computed like this:\n",
        "\n",
        "Spectral dependence of the AOT K (λ)=$\\frac{\\tau(\\lambda)}{\\tau}(550)$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$K(\\lambda) = \\sum_{u}^{}{K_{u}(\\lambda)X}_{u}$\n",
        "\n",
        "Single scattering albedo:\n",
        "\n",
        "$\\varpi_{0}(\\lambda) = \\sum_{u}^{}{\\varpi_{0}^{u}{(\\lambda)X}_{u}}$\n",
        "\n",
        "Phase function:\n",
        "\n",
        "$P(\\theta,\\lambda) = \\sum_{u}^{}{P_{u}(\\theta,\\lambda)X_{u}}$\n",
        "\n",
        "And the derived asymmetry parameter:\n",
        "\n",
        "$g(\\lambda) = \\frac{1}{2}\\int_{- 1}^{1}{\\mu P(\\mu,\\lambda)}d\\mu$ with $\\mu = cos(\\theta)$\n",
        "\n",
        "These aerosol optical properties are plotted in Figure 15 and Figure 16.\n",
        "\n",
        "| ![](./media/media/image29.png){width=\"3.5984251968503935in\" height=\"2.3976377952755907in\"} |\n",
        "|:---|\n",
        "| ![](./media/media/image30.png){width=\"3.5984251968503935in\" height=\"2.3976377952755907in\"} |\n",
        "| ![](./media/media/image31.png){width=\"3.5984251968503935in\" height=\"2.3976377952755907in\"} |\n",
        "\n",
        "Figure : OPAC Aerosols components optical properties with RH=80% at the Proba-V spectral bands\n",
        "\n",
        "| ![](./media/media/image32.png){width=\"3.5984251968503935in\" height=\"2.3976377952755907in\"} |\n",
        "|:---|\n",
        "| ![](./media/media/image33.png){width=\"3.5984251968503935in\" height=\"2.3976377952755907in\"} |\n",
        "| ![](./media/media/image34.png){width=\"3.5984251968503935in\" height=\"2.3976377952755907in\"} |\n",
        "\n",
